Disk Forensics > [T2]: Extracting Startup and shutdown time

(4) Startup and shutdown time

 
The last shutdown time can be found at System\ControlSet001\Control\Windows key. 

 

Values stored in Windows key - (zoom in)

  1. Startup and shutdown registry key.
  2. Startup and shutdown registry key path.
  3. ShutdownTime value contains the last shutdown time encoded using Windows FILETIME timestamp. You can decode it using Registry Explorer's Data Interpreter.

You can also keep in mind that if you have the "fast startup" option enabled in your power settings, which means that Windows is not fully shut down but instead partially hibernated. This can cause discrepancies with the shutdown time in the registry, as it may reflect a time that was long ago.

You can utilize Windows event logs to get a detailed view of startup and shutdown history. In particular, three specific event logs: 1074, 6005, and 6006.

 

System.evtx - (zoom in)

 

  1. System Log -> Event ID 1074 shows the shutdown Type ( e.g., power off, shutdown, restart) and the process which initiated the shutdown.
  2. System Log -> Event ID 6005 (start) / 6006 (stop): indicates the start and stops of the event log service, which can be used to conclude shutdown and boot time. The event log service stops when the system shuts down and starts when the system boots up.

But what about situations where the computer was not shut down gracefully? We cannot use the above event logs to track boot-up and shutdowns because they will not be generated in case of an ungraceful shutdown. In that case, we can search for event ID 41, which is logged when the system reboots without cleanly shutting down first. This error could result from a system crash or losing power unexpectedly. In addition, event ID 6008 is logged when the system experiences an unexpected shutdown (e.g., Hardware failure).

 

Nirsoft's TurnedOnTimeView tool is an excellent tool to automate the exercise of going through these event logs, parsing them, and providing a detailed and nice view of shutdown and bootup activities.
